@c page
@node overview
@chapter Overview of the package


@noindent
@value{PACKAGE} is a distribution of Scheme language libraries for
@rnrs{6} Scheme, targeting Ypsilon and Ikarus.  This document describes
the project building and installation infrastructure, which is used by
almost all the projects in the distribution.

Almost all the projects in Nausicaa are pure Scheme; the Stubs projects
collects adapter C language libraries.  Access to foreign shared
libraries is written with the Foreign Functions Interface (@ffi{})
provided by the Scheme implementation.


@menu
* overview conventions::        Conventions.
@end menu


@c page
@node overview conventions
@section Conventions


This guide tries to stick to the following naming conventions:

@table @emph
@item file name
@itemx directory name
it is the last component of the file or directory identifier; the name
of the file in @file{/bin/bash} is @code{bash}, while the name of the
directory in @file{/usr/local} is @code{local};

@item file pathname
@itemx directory pathname
it is a file or directory identifier that includes a name and a
directory part; @file{/bin/bash} is a file pathname and
@file{/usr/local} is a directory pathname;

@item file basename
@itemx directory basename
it is a file or directory name with the extension stripped (including
the dot); the basename of the file in @file{/etc/lilo.conf} is
@code{lilo}, while the basename of the directory in @file{/etc/rc.d} is
@code{rc};

@item file rootname
@itemx directory rootname
it is a file or directory pathname with the extension stripped
(including the dot); the rootname of the file in @file{/etc/lilo.conf}
is @code{/etc/lilo}, while the rootname of the directory in
@file{/etc/rc.d} is @code{/etc/rc};

@item path
it is a list of directory pathnames to look into when searching for a
file or directory name.
@end table


@c page
@node conf
@chapter Configuration


The configuration of a project for building, installation and binary
package creation is managed with @gnu{} Autoconf.  Each project
subdirectory has a @command{configure} script that must be run to
initialise the infrastructure.

Let's take the @code{scmobj} project as example; we should do this:

@example
$ tar --extract --bzip2 --file=nausicaa-0.1d2.tar.bz2
$ cd nausicaa-0.1d2
$ cd scmobj
$ mkdir "=build"
$ cd "=build"
$ ../configure
@end example

@noindent
then we are ready to apply the @command{make} program to the
@file{Makefile}.


