@section Command line options


@deffn {Autoconf Macro} NAUSICAA_ENABLE_OPTION (@var{variable}, @var{identifier}, @var{default}, @var{checking-description}, @var{option-description})
Define an enable/disable command line option for @configure{}.  Set
@var{variable} to @code{yes} if the enable option is used, to @code{no}
if the disable option is used.

@var{variable} is an output variable, it is used as argument for
@code{AC_SUBST}.

@var{identifier} is the key used to define the options, which will be
@code{--enable-@var{identifier}} and @code{--disable-@var{identifier}}.

@var{default} is the default value for @var{variable} if neither the
enable nor the disable options are used.  It must be @code{yes} or
@code{no}.

@var{checking-description} is a description of the feature that is shown
as log message when @configure{} is executed.  It will show as:

@example
checking @var{checking-description} ... yes
@end example

@var{option-description} is the description of the feature that is shown
when @configure{} is executed with the @code{--help} option.

Usage example:

@example
NAUSICAA_ENABLE_OPTION([nausicaa_ENABLE_FASL],[fasl],[no],
   [whether compiled files will be built and installed],
   [enable installation of precompiled libraries])
@end example

@noindent
this defines the options @option{--enable-fasl} and
@option{--disable-fasl}, that can be used to configure the output
variable @code{nausicaa_ENABLE_FASL}.  The default is @code{no}.  The
checking message will show as:

@example
checking whether compiled files will be built and installed ... no
@end example

@noindent
and the help screen will include the lines:

@example
--disable-fasl   enable installation of precompiled libraries
                (default: yes)
@end example

When the default is @code{yes}: it is better to write
@var{option-description} as a description of the disable option, because
that is what the user does to change the default.
@end deffn


@deffn {Autoconf Macro} NAUSICAA_WITH_OPTION (@var{variable}, @var{identifier}, @var{default}, @var{checking-description}, @var{option-description})
Define a @code{--with-} command line option for @configure{}.  Set
@var{variable} to the argument given to the option.

@var{variable} is an output variable, it is used as argument for
@code{AC_SUBST}.

@var{identifier} is the key used to define the option, which will be
@code{--with-@var{identifier}}.

@var{default} is the default value for @var{variable} if the option is
not used.

@var{checking-description} is a description of the feature that is shown
as log message when @configure{} is executed.  It will show as:

@example
checking @var{checking-description} ... @var{default}
@end example

@var{option-description} is the description of the feature that is shown
when @configure{} is executed with the @code{--help} option.

Usage example:

@example
NAUSICAA_WITH_OPTION([package_BUILD_VERSION],[build-version],[1nau],
   [binary package build revision tag],
   [select binary package build revision tag])
@end example

@noindent
this defines the options @option{--with-build-version}, that can be used
to configure the output variable @code{package_BUILD_VERSION}.  The
default is @code{1nau}.  The checking message will show as:

@example
checking binary package build revision tag ... 1nau
@end example

@noindent
and the help screen will include the lines:

@example
--with-build-version    select binary package build revision tag
                        (default: 1nau)
@end example
@end deffn


